\subsection{The Thermal Shift and Roughness Scaling}
\label{subsec:thermal_shift_gspt}

The active critical manifold $\mathcal{M}_0^{\text{act}}$ defines an elliptic paraboloid in the $(U, V, e)$ coordinates for any fixed surface temperature $T_s$. The spatial and dynamic properties of this manifold are highly sensitive to both surface radiative cooling and local roughness characteristics:

\paragraph{The Thermal Shift Paradox.}
During nocturnal radiative cooling, the surface skin temperature cools rapidly ($T_s \downarrow$). Because the stability function satisfies $\partial G(T_s) / \partial T_s < 0$, cooling increases the buoyant destruction term ($G(T_s) \uparrow$), which in turn drives the net environmental metric downward ($\Delta(\mathbf{y}) \downarrow$).

Geometrically, this cooling translates the paraboloid critical manifold $\mathcal{M}_0^{\text{act}}$ vertically downward along the TKE axis. The volume of active phase space where $e > 0$ contracts, forcing the SBL toward decay.

\paragraph{Roughness Scaling and the FLOSS Regime.}
The drag coefficient $\gamma$ scales directly with the surface momentum roughness length $z_{0m}$ via classic log-profile theory:
\begin{equation}
\gamma \propto \left[ \ln\left( \frac{z_{\text{ref}}}{z_{0m}} \right) \right]^{-2}.
\end{equation}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{FLOSS (Fluxes Over Snow Surfaces):} Smooth snow features an exceptionally tiny roughness length ($z_{0m} \sim 10^{-4}\,\text{m}$). This minimizes frictional drag, suppressing mechanical shear production ($\gamma \to 0$). The critical manifold paraboloid contracts dramatically, requiring much larger geostrophic wind speeds ($\sqrt{U_g^2 + V_g^2}$) to sustain active turbulence before the manifold translates below the $e=0$ threshold.
    \item \textbf{Grasslands (CASES99):} The larger roughness of sparse vegetation ($z_{0m} \sim 10^{-2}\,\text{m}$) enhances shear production, expanding the paraboloid envelope and permitting active turbulence to persist under weaker geostrophic winds.
\end{itemize}